  "success": true,
  "output": "This is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (114 configured ATS sources, SQLite dedup store, no React/frontend). Here's what I found, ranked by impact.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (biggest finding)\n\n`Store.diff()` loops over every fetched job and issues one `SELECT` (plus one `INSERT`/`UPDATE`) per row, inside a Python `for` loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith 114 sources configured — several with `max_pages` of 30–40 at 10–16 jobs/page (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Google, Optiver) — a single run can push thousands of rows through this loop, each a separate statement round-trip. It runs on a 12h cron, so this cost repeats every cycle and only grows as `jobs.db` accumulates.\n\n**Fix**: batch-load existing hashes once, diff in memory, then write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for chunk_start in range(0, len(jobs), 500):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = jobs[chunk_start:chunk_start + 500]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        rows = cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\",\n            [j.key for j in chunk],\n        ).fetchall()\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in rows})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = job.to_row()  # hash computed once, reused below\n        row[\"now\"] = now\n        prior_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prior_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append(row)\n        elif prior_hash != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append(row)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/500) reads + 3 batched writes.\n\nAlso add `self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")` in `Store.__init__` — safe default for a write-heavy dedup store, and add an index for the other hot query:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n`added_since()` (store.py:111-119) currently sorts/filters `first_seen` with no supporting index — full table scan on every `db-new` call.\n\n## 2. React re-renders — not applicable\n\nThere's no frontend in this repo (no `.tsx`/`.jsx`, no `package.json` with React). Skipping this category rather than force a fit — if you have a separate dashboard repo, point me at it.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-27`\n\n`_compile()` recompiles the same include/exclude regex patterns **for every single job**, since `match()` is called once per job inside the `filter_jobs` list comprehension:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFor thousands of jobs × N keyword patterns, that's needless `re.compile` calls (compilation is much more expensive than matching). Fix: compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in rules.get(\"locations\") or []]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=(), cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n**`Job.content_hash`** (models.py:66-69) is a plain `@property` recomputing SHA-256 over `title|location|url|department` every access — and it's accessed 2-3x per job across one run: once in `Store.diff`'s old vs. new comparison, again inside `to_row()` for the INSERT/UPDATE, and again in `notify_webhook`'s `to_row()` call. Since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work directly (no `__dict__`), but the batched-diff rewrite above already fixes this incidentally — `to_row()` is now called once per job and the resulting dict (with hash) is reused for both the diff comparison and the write.\n\n## 4. Memory footprint — `fetchers.py:767-788`, `pipeline.py:30`\n\n`fetch_all` gathers **every** source's full job list (including the `raw` payload dict per `Job`) into one big Python list before filtering or diffing runs at all:\n\n```python\njobs = await fetch_all(sources, concurrency=cfg[\"concurrency\"])   # everything, in memory\njobs = filter_jobs(jobs, cfg[\"filters\"])                          # filtered after full materialization\n```\n\nNot a \"leak\" in the classic sense (process is short-lived and exits), but for 114 sources with some boards in the thousands of postings, peak RSS holds all raw JSON blobs simultaneously even though most are discarded seconds later by `filter_jobs`/`store.diff`. If this pipeline's node count or `max_pages` config grows, consider filtering per-source as each `fetch_source` future completes rather than after the full `gather`:\n\n```python\nasync def one(src: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    async with sem:\n        try:\n            jobs = await fetch_source(client, src)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! {src['ats']}:{...} failed: {e}\")\n            return []\n        return filter_jobs(jobs, cfg_filters)   # drop non-matches immediately, don't hold raw\n```\nThis caps peak memory to the largest single source rather than the sum of all sources.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunities\n\n- **HTTP conditional requests**: none of the `_simple`/bespoke fetchers send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`. Greenhouse/Lever/Ashby etc. support ETags; on a 12h cron against boards that change slowly, this would cut bandwidth and avoid re-parsing unchanged payloads (though the dedup-by-hash logic already absorbs most of the downstream cost).\n- **Meta's token scrape** (`fetch_meta`, fetchers.py:537-574) re-fetches and re-regexes the careers page for `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens every run — unavoidable per-run since tokens rotate, not a real caching opportunity here, just flagging it's already about as cheap as it can be.\n\n## Summary priority\n1. Batch `Store.diff()` — biggest win, directly proportional to `114 sources × job count` per scheduled run.\n2. Hoist regex compilation out of `filter_jobs`'s per-job loop.\n3. Add `idx_jobs_first_seen` + WAL mode.\n4. Stream filter-per-source instead of materializing everything before filtering, if source count/board sizes keep growing.\n\nWant me to implement the `Store.diff` batching and the filter fix now?\n",
